@dfellis, I do like the benefits of immutable objects in terms of reasoning about code.

If you do want to modify the object, a user can always make a mutable copy. I can't immediately think of any use cases where the copy would be performance limiting. (An explicit copy also makes the intention of the code more clear!)

In terms of giving the user the option, I suppose we could provide mutable and immutable versions of the APIs.

