In this case, I'm considering it less a mutation and more a "default value with special case":

```go
x := defaultValue
if condition {
  x = override
}
```

This case just happens to include validation before the override.

The other patter is indeed:

```
var x Type
if cond {
  x = a
} else {
  x = b
}
```

Which is closer to a "paragraph" that calculates the value of x. I read that closer to a block expression in some languages, e.g.

```
x = if cond { a } else { b };
```

However, for this case, we have a bit of extra validation we need to do on one of the arms of the if statement, which makes sense to do at the same time we're calculating filterName.

The following would also be okay:

```go
var filterName string
if cmd.orgName == "" {
  filterName = userName
} else {
  // TODO: sliceContains check here
  filterName = cmd.orgName
}
```

Depends on whether you read it as "a block that calculates the value of filterName" or "filterName is always userName except if an orgName was provided". I don't have a strong preference between the two.

